	H2 Getting Bloom on Linux
	P Bloom 3.7 is available for Ubuntu Precise, Trusty, and Xenial.  It can also be installed on Wasta 12, Wasta 14, and Wasta 16. You are welcome to try other versions of Linux but we cannot promise to support them.

	H3 Step 1: Try to install the Bloom Desktop program
	pre
		| sudo apt-get install bloom-desktop
	P If this succeeds, you can skip to step 4 below (you are already a user of SIL software).  If this fails because of authorization issues or a missing sudo program, you need to consult with the local Linux administrator.  If this fails because apt-get cannot locate the package, then the following steps are needed.
	H3 Step 2: Add the SIL repository to your system
	H4 (for precise or wasta12):
	pre wget -qO - http://packages.sil.org/sil.gpg | sudo apt-key add -
	pre sudo add-apt-repository "deb http://packages.sil.org/ubuntu precise main"
	pre sudo apt-get update
	H4 (for trusty or wasta14):
	pre wget -qO - http://packages.sil.org/sil.gpg | sudo apt-key add -
	pre sudo add-apt-repository "deb http://packages.sil.org/ubuntu trusty main"
	pre sudo apt-get update
	H4 (for xenial or wasta16):
	pre wget -qO - http://packages.sil.org/sil.gpg | sudo apt-key add -
	pre sudo add-apt-repository "deb http://packages.sil.org/ubuntu xenial main"
	pre sudo apt-get update
	H3 Step 3: Get the release of the  Bloom Desktop program
	pre
		| sudo apt-get install bloom-desktop
	H3 Step 4: Copy the desktop launcher to your local area
	pre cp -i /usr/share/applications/bloom.desktop ~/Desktop
	pre chmod +x ~/Desktop/bloom.desktop
	H3 Step 5: Launch the Application
	H4 (mouse)
	P Double click the desktop launcher icon
	H4 (keyboard)
	P Type the name of the program in a command window or into the dashboard or startup menu
	pre
		| bloom

	P Once Bloom has been installed, updates will be downloaded and installed the same way your system is already installing updates to other software.

	H2 Note to current users of SIL software (December 2016)
	P For security reasons, the SIL repository is getting a new
		strong
			|  public key
		|  in January 2017.  Although the developers are making an effort to make this seamless for current users, it is possible that attempts to update or install software from the SIL repository may fail due to a mismatched key after January 1, 2017.  If that happens, the solution is simply to run the first command given above for adding the SIL repository to your system.  This will add the new repository public key to your system.
